Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
bit_blasted_port_style(25.10)                    bit_blasted_port_style(25.10)

Name
       bit_blasted_port_style

Syntax
        bit_blasted_port_style %s_%d

       Type: String

       Default: %s_%d, persistent

       This global variable is used to define the bus bit blasted port name.

       Specifies  the  naming style to be used if mapped ports are bit blasted
       with the command bitblast_ports. The values of this global need to con-
       tain elements %s and %d.

       The following rules apply:

              * A port name always starts with the base name  (represented  by
                %s)

              * The suffix is appended to the base name to form port name, ac-
                cording to the format specified in the global value.

              * %d represents the bit information.

Example
       The default of %s_%d will convert a bus-bit A[0] to A_0.

       If  you  want to keep the original bus-bit name but have it turned into
       an escaped scalar name you can use:

       set_db bit_blasted_port_style {%s\[%d\]}

       This will convert a bus-bit A[0] to an escaped scalar  name  A\[0\]  in
       Tcl,  so  the  port  .name  would be "A[0]", the .escaped_name would be
       "A\[0\]", the dual-ported-object name would look like {port:top/A\[0\]}
       with Tcl adding the {} around it to protect the \ chars, and  the  Ver-
       ilog port would look like "\A[0] ".

       One  advantage  of  this  is that SDC commands and Innovus Tcl commands
       that use port names with A[0] will still "soft-match"  the  new  A\[0\]
       name,  so  they do not have to change. However, using escaped names may
       require careful Tcl scripting to make sure  you  do  not  inadvertently
       lose the escaped \ chars when you want them.

Related Information
              * bitblast_ports

